{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7772e41c-c3cb-4e0b-80ab-80dcbb07a4fa","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project itself is simple and compiles fast. The 2-4s overhead on `dotnet build` comes from **MSBuild process startup + NuGet restore evaluation** on every invocation — costs that Visual Studio avoids by keeping MSBuild running in-process.\n\n## Recommendations (most impactful first)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the build host alive between edits — no repeated startup cost:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Skip restore when packages haven't changed\nRestore runs by default on every `dotnet build` and adds ~0.5-1s:\n```\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### 3. Enable the MSBuild Server (.NET 8+)\nThis is the CLI equivalent of what VS does — keeps an MSBuild node running between invocations:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\n\n### 4. Enable node reuse\nEnsure MSBuild worker nodes persist between builds:\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0   # 0 = reuse enabled (the default, but verify)\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Technique | Saves | Effort |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch build` | ~2-3s per build | Just use it |\n| `--no-restore` | ~0.5-1s | Add to alias/script |\n| MSBuild Server | ~1-2s startup | Set env var |\n| Node reuse | ~0.5s | Verify not disabled |\n\nFor quick edit-build-test cycles, **`dotnet watch build`** is the single biggest win — it mirrors VS's always-warm behavior from the terminal.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e62f00d5-2474-41de-add0-a57f678b2d0f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds) even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified that analyzers aren't the issue and that incremental targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server that keeps the process warm, avoiding startup and project re-evaluation costs. The CLI equivalent is the **MSBuild Server** (also called the \"build server\" or \"node reuse\" features).\n\nHere are the main recommendations:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet build-server`** - .NET 8+ supports the MSBuild build server which keeps the MSBuild process running between invocations. \n\nTo enable it, I can set the environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or use the `-tl` option, and I should also ensure node reuse is enabled by not setting `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1`.\n\n2. **Skip unnecessary restore steps** - If dependencies haven't changed, using `dotnet build --no-restore` avoids that overhead.\n\n3. **Try graph-based builds** - The `/graph` option can improve incremental performance by better understanding build dependencies.\n\n4. **Use `dotnet watch`** - For development, `dotnet watch build` keeps the process warm between changes instead of spinning up a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe core insight is that Visual Studio stays fast because it keeps MSBuild running in-process, while CLI invocations have to start a fresh process every time. The MSBuild server in .NET 8+ addresses this by maintaining a persistent server between builds. For .NET 8 and later, I can enable the MSBuild server to keep the build process running between invocations, which eliminates startup overhead on subsequent builds.","outputTokens":1249},"id":"e8c89c6c-c056-403c-b058-3111836471cd","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:50:00.125Z","parentId":"15fff9b9-d9c1-4049-b986-400ed8a584c7"}
